You need to buy the updated drivers to view ALL DVD's on the PS2. The drivers are sold with the official Sony PS2 DVD remote. Not so bad for $27 or whatever, plus it is a very cool remote. But some of my friends have had trouble playing recent DVD's, and getting the latest DVD drivers with the remote fixed them right up.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Uhm, I'm not sure who told you that exactly.  I've had my PS for awhile, and I've never had trouble watching the new DVD's.  Infact I just watched American Pie 2 last night on my PS2.  Maybe my PS2 is just speshul.  :P<br>
<br>
<br>
Now to the Xbox fans:<br>
<br>
I agree that the Xbox graphics are superior to the ps2 graphics.  Halo, and DOA3 are very nice looking games.  But graphics don't make the game.  I sure many of you all enjoy sitting back and playing old school tetris, and old school pong.  I know I do because they were well designed games.  But they aren't exactly the prettiest games on the market.<br>
<br>
I remember reading someone saying that they could grasp the controls very well in Halo.  When I said that Halo should have been made for the computer, its not because FPS games are hard to play with a controller.  Its because you need to have quite a bit of power to make a FPS game successful.  The type of power that a computer can offer.<br>
<br>
The last successful FPS single player game was Half-life.  Eventually people stopped playing the single player modes and started playing the multiplayer deathmatches, and the multiplayer mods -- namely counterstrike.  Intense multiplayer battle is just not something that a console can offer the gamer.  Mods are another thing that consoles can't offer a gamer.  I think that Halo would have made for a wonderful teambased FPS game using dedicated TCP/IP connections.  Obviously after you beat Halo, how many times to you plan to beat it again?  I don't see much replay value in Halo, nor do I see the ability to expand it to keep gamers intrested.  So for those of you who don't understand why I think Halo should have been a computer game; that is my reason.<br>
<br>
Graphics in Halo are nice, but it doesn't make it a good game.  A good game to me entails some sort of replay value.  Something that I don't see Halo offering.<br>
<br>
Now for DOA3.  DOA sells itself via sexual inuendos.  Not that its a bad way to market a game.  However it does not mean that its an extroadanary fighting game.  The graphics are very nice on DOA3.  I like the huge envirnmental fighting areas, and the tag team moves.  However, I don't find it a very challenging game.  Maybe its because I've been playing fighting games since they've first came out, or maybe its because the moves are easy.  Either way I had more trouble learning and mastering the moves in Tekken Tag Tournament, than I did in DOA3.  Also, DOA3 strikes me as a button pushing game -- as all the other DOA games have been.  Button pushing games are good if your that type of player, but I'm not that type of player.<br>
<br>
Now to the original poster:<br>
<br>
If your looking to buy the right system, my suggestion would be to get together with friends who have one system to check that system out, then get together with friends who have the other system to check that system out.  Visit the IGN website check out some of the games, and visit other gamer boards to see what people are saying about the systems. <p><body><center><img src="http://people.mw.mediaone.net/danwill100/KeraaSig.jpg"</img></center>
